By reference then to Aristotle's account of the latter, it will plainly appear that he and Locke mean two very different things by Definition. With the former, it is an investigation os the objective cause of a phenomenon3 with the latter, an analysis of the subjective impression which that phenomenon produces in the mind. The idea of an interception of light is not part of the idea eclipse‚ but the one phenomenon is the physical antecedent and cause of the other. Inquiries of this kind are still classed among the most important problems of Physica] Science. What, for example, is light? Is it a succession of material particles‚ or the undulations of an elastic medium? The solution of this question would not be a Definition in Locke’s sense of the w0rd3 i. e. it would not be an analysis of the idea of light produced in the mind by sensation. The same ina-y be said of colour. The mental sensation of whiteness or redness is altogether unaffected by the researches of Optios. The external cause of colour, regarded as a quality of bodies, falls directly within the province of the Soiencee. The de- termination of such problems will be, in Aristotle⁷s sense of the term, Definition.
